---
import ChapterDivider from '../components/ChapterDivider.astro';
import HeroSection from '../components/HeroSection.astro';
import ReferenceSup from '../components/ReferenceSup.astro';
import SideNav from '../components/SideNav.astro';
import '../styles/global.css'
---

<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="utf-8" />
		<link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
		<link rel="icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
		<meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
		<title>Underage Prosecution Article</title>
	</head>
	<body class="bg-[#f7f5f2] text-black antialiased">
		<header
			id="site-header"
			class="fixed inset-x-0 top-0 z-50 border-b border-black/10 bg-[#f7f5f2]/95 shadow-sm backdrop-blur"
			style="opacity: 0;"
		>
			<div class="relative mx-auto flex max-w-6xl items-center justify-between px-6 py-4">
				<p id="current-chapter" class="pointer-events-none absolute left-1/2 hidden -translate-x-1/2 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-black/70 transition-all duration-250 md:block">
					Chapter 1 - Foundations of Juvenile Responsibility
				</p>
				<nav aria-label="Main navigation" class="ml-auto text-sm font-medium text-black/50">
					<a class="transition hover:text-black" href="#references">References</a>
				</nav>
			</div>
		</header>

		<SideNav />

		<main>
			<HeroSection />

			<section id="article" class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 py-24">
				<article class="space-y-10 text-[1.125rem] leading-[1.85] text-black">
					<p>
						Underage prosecution sits at the intersection of public safety, developmental psychology, and legal
						ethics. Courts are often asked to evaluate not only what happened, but also who the accused person was
						at the time of the event. Adolescents process risk, peer pressure, and long-term consequences
						differently than adults, which means legal systems must decide how punishment and intervention should be
						calibrated.
						<ReferenceSup
							number={1}
							href="https://www.ojjdp.gov/ojstatbb/structure_process/qa04102.asp?qaDate=2024"
							label="Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention - Juvenile Court Process Overview"
						/>
					</p>

					<!-- pull quote -->
					<div class="py-4">
						<div class="mb-6 w-20 border-t-2 border-[#c1121f]"></div>
						<p class="text-[1.35rem] font-bold leading-snug text-black">
							The juvenile system is built on a single premise: young people can change.
						</p>
					</div>

					<p>
						In many jurisdictions, proceedings emphasize education plans, counseling, restorative practices, and
						family participation over incarceration. This model assumes that timely support can reduce repeat
						offenses and improve long-term outcomes. It also acknowledges that behavior in adolescence is not
						always a reliable predictor of adult conduct.
						<ReferenceSup
							number={2}
							href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK53420/"
							label="National Academies - Reforming Juvenile Justice: A Developmental Approach"
						/>
					</p>
				</article>
			</section>

			<div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 pb-24">
				<figure>
					<img
						src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1521587760476-6c12a4b040da?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1400&q=80"
						alt="Rows of legal books in a law library"
						class="w-full object-cover"
						style="height: 420px;"
						loading="lazy"
					/>
					<figcaption class="mt-3 text-[0.8rem] leading-relaxed text-black/40">
						Photo: Unsplash / <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/1521587760476" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-black">Alfons Morales</a> — Law library collection, used for editorial illustration.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<ChapterDivider id="chapter-2" chapter="Chapter 2" title="When Does a Case Move to Adult Court?" />

			<section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 py-24">
				<article class="space-y-10 text-[1.125rem] leading-[1.85] text-black">
					<p>
						Some cases involve severe harm or repeated violent conduct. Prosecutors may petition to move a matter
						into adult court, arguing that the seriousness of the offense outweighs the protections of the juvenile
						framework. Transfer decisions are typically influenced by age, prior record, weapon use, public impact,
						and expert evaluations regarding maturity and amenability to treatment.
					</p>

					<!-- pull quote -->
					<div class="py-4">
						<div class="mb-6 w-20 border-t-2 border-[#c1121f]"></div>
						<p class="text-[1.35rem] font-bold leading-snug text-black">
							The core question is always the same: can accountability be achieved without discarding development?
						</p>
					</div>

					<p>
						Judges reviewing transfer requests assess whether juvenile court resources can realistically address
						the specific conduct at issue. This includes reviewing intervention programs, school records,
						probation history, and psychological assessments.
					</p>
				</article>
			</section>

			<div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 pb-24">
				<figure>
					<img
						src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1450101499163-c8848c66ca85?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1400&q=80"
						alt="Courtroom bench and legal documents"
						class="w-full object-cover"
						style="height: 420px;"
						loading="lazy"
					/>
				<figcaption class="mt-3 text-[0.8rem] leading-relaxed text-black/40">
						Photo: Unsplash / <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/1450101499163" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-black">Scott Graham</a> — Legal documents and courtroom materials, used for editorial illustration.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<ChapterDivider id="chapter-3" chapter="Chapter 3" title="Balancing Accountability and Rehabilitation" />

			<section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 py-24">
				<article class="space-y-10 text-[1.125rem] leading-[1.85] text-black">
					<p>
						Defense advocacy in underage prosecution often focuses on context: trauma exposure, educational gaps,
						unmet mental health needs, and unstable home environments. These factors do not erase accountability,
						but they can shape sentencing alternatives. Programs that combine supervision with structured support
						often report better outcomes than punitive responses alone.
					</p>

					<!-- pull quote -->
					<div class="py-4">
						<div class="mb-6 w-20 border-t-2 border-[#c1121f]"></div>
						<p class="text-[1.35rem] font-bold leading-snug text-black">
							Systems that align accountability with rehabilitation respond to serious conduct without abandoning
							the realities of adolescence.
						</p>
					</div>

					<p>
						Policy debates continue over where to draw the line between deterrence and compassion. Victim-centered
						voices call for meaningful consequences and recognition of harm, while reform advocates emphasize the
						capacity of youth to change. Legislatures and courts increasingly use outcome data to evaluate which
						approaches lower recidivism and improve community safety.
						<ReferenceSup
							number={3}
							href="https://www.sentencingproject.org/reports/youth-justice-by-the-numbers/"
							label="The Sentencing Project - Youth Justice By The Numbers"
						/>
					</p>

					<p>
						A modern framework for underage prosecution requires nuance: clear legal standards, consistent due
						process, and evidence-based interventions. When these elements align, courts can respond to serious
						conduct without discarding the developmental realities of adolescence.
					</p>

					<figure>
						<img
							src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1589578527966-fdac0f44566c?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1400&q=80"
							alt="Person writing notes during legal case preparation"
							class="w-full object-cover"
							style="height: 420px;"
							loading="lazy"
						/>
						<figcaption class="mt-3 text-[0.8rem] leading-relaxed text-black/40">
							Photo: Unsplash / <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/1589578527966" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-black">Sora Shimazaki</a> — Case preparation notes, used for editorial illustration.
						</figcaption>
					</figure>
				</article>
			</section>

			<section id="references" class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 py-24">
				<h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-black">References</h3>
				<ol class="mt-6 list-decimal space-y-4 pl-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-black">
					<li>
						<a class="underline hover:text-[#780000]" href="https://www.ojjdp.gov/ojstatbb/structure_process/qa04102.asp?qaDate=2024" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
							Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention - Juvenile Court Process Overview
						</a>
					</li>
					<li>
						<a class="underline hover:text-[#780000]" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK53420/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
							National Academies - Reforming Juvenile Justice: A Developmental Approach
						</a>
					</li>
					<li>
						<a class="underline hover:text-[#780000]" href="https://www.sentencingproject.org/reports/youth-justice-by-the-numbers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
							The Sentencing Project - Youth Justice By The Numbers
						</a>
					</li>
				</ol>
			</section>
		</main>

		<footer class="border-t border-black/10 bg-[#f7f5f2]">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-6xl flex-col gap-3 px-6 py-8 text-sm text-black/40 md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between">
				<p>Underage Prosecution Website Skeleton</p>
				<p>Updated for legal article structure and scroll-aware navigation</p>
			</div>
		</footer>

		<script>
			const header = document.querySelector('#site-header');
			const hero = document.querySelector('#hero');
			const chapterDividers = document.querySelectorAll('.chapter-divider');
			const chapterLabel = document.querySelector('#current-chapter');
			const chapterMap = [
				{ id: 'article', label: 'Chapter 1 - Foundations of Juvenile Responsibility' },
				{ id: 'chapter-2', label: 'Chapter 2 - When Does a Case Move to Adult Court?' },
				{ id: 'chapter-3', label: 'Chapter 3 - Balancing Accountability and Rehabilitation' },
				{ id: 'references', label: 'References' },
			];

			let heroInView = true;
			let headerIsVisible = false;

			const updateHeaderVisibility = () => {
				if (!header) return;
				const h = header as HTMLElement;
				const headerH = h.clientHeight;
				const dividerAtHeader = Array.from(chapterDividers).some((d) => {
					const rect = d.getBoundingClientRect();
					return rect.top < headerH && rect.bottom > 0;
				});

				const shouldShow = !heroInView && !dividerAtHeader;

				if (shouldShow && !headerIsVisible) {
					headerIsVisible = true;
					h.style.transition = 'opacity 450ms ease-out';
					requestAnimationFrame(() => requestAnimationFrame(() => { h.style.opacity = '1'; }));
				} else if (!shouldShow && headerIsVisible) {
					headerIsVisible = false;
					if (dividerAtHeader) {
						// Divider is physically covering the header — hide instantly
						h.style.transition = 'none';
						h.style.opacity = '0';
					} else {
						// Hero scrolling back into view — fade out
						h.style.transition = 'opacity 350ms ease-in';
						h.style.opacity = '0';
					}
				}
			};

			if (header && hero) {
				const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
					(entries) => {
						const [entry] = entries;
						heroInView = entry.isIntersecting;
						updateHeaderVisibility();
					},
					{
						threshold: 0.2,
					}
				);

				observer.observe(hero);
			}

			if (chapterDividers.length > 0) {
				const chapterObserver = new IntersectionObserver(
					(entries) => {
						entries.forEach((entry) => {
							entry.target.classList.toggle('in-view', entry.isIntersecting);
						});
					},
					{
						threshold: 0.45,
					}
				);

				chapterDividers.forEach((divider) => {
					chapterObserver.observe(divider);
				});
			}

			const updateChapterLabel = () => {
				if (!chapterLabel) return;

				let active = chapterMap[0];

				chapterMap.forEach((item) => {
					const el = document.getElementById(item.id);
					if (!el) return;
					const rect = el.getBoundingClientRect();
					// For chapter dividers, only trigger once their top edge has reached
					// the top of the viewport (halfway through scrolling the full-screen divider).
					// For regular sections, trigger when their top passes 35% down the screen.
					const triggered = el.classList.contains('chapter-divider')
						? rect.top <= 0
						: rect.top <= window.innerHeight * 0.35;
					if (triggered) active = item;
				});

				const current = chapterLabel.textContent?.trim();
				if (current === active.label) return;

				if (!headerIsVisible) {
					// Header is off-screen — swap text silently with no animation
					chapterLabel.textContent = active.label;
					return;
				}

				chapterLabel.classList.add('opacity-0');
				setTimeout(() => {
					chapterLabel.textContent = active.label;
					chapterLabel.classList.remove('opacity-0');
				}, 200);
			};

			const setupReferenceCopy = () => {
				const copyButtons = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('[data-copy-link]');
				copyButtons.forEach((button) => {
					button.addEventListener('click', async () => {
						const link = button.getAttribute('data-copy-link');
						if (!link) return;
						await navigator.clipboard.writeText(link);
						button.classList.add('bg-black', 'text-white');
						const status = button.parentElement?.querySelector('[data-copy-status]');
						status?.classList.remove('opacity-0');
						button.blur();
						setTimeout(() => {
							button.classList.remove('bg-black', 'text-white');
							status?.classList.add('opacity-0');
						}, 1200);
					});
				});
			};

			window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { updateChapterLabel(); updateHeaderVisibility(); }, { passive: true });
			window.addEventListener('load', () => { updateChapterLabel(); updateHeaderVisibility(); });
			updateChapterLabel();
			updateHeaderVisibility();
			setupReferenceCopy();
		</script>
	</body>
</html>
